        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-02-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-02-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="141"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d141">
                <head>141. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RWP1"
                        type="from">Rogers</persName> to the President’s Assistant for National
                    Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="to"
                        >Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d141fn1">Source:
                        National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>
                        Office Files, Box 148, State/WH Relationship, Vol. 5. Secret; Eyes
                        Only.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-02-10">February 10, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have reviewed the cables referred to in your memorandum of February 5.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d141fn2">
                        <ref target="#d139">Document 139.</ref>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0330" n="299" xml:id="pg_299"/>
                <p>The applicable part of the President’s two directives to which you refer is that
                    governing official communications, which states: “All official communications
                    with policy implications must be cleared with the White House. When in doubt,
                    the rule is that messages will be so cleared….”<note n="3" xml:id="d141fn3"
                        >Ellipsis in the source text.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Early in the Administration I established procedures within the Department
                    concerning clearances with the White House. These procedures fully accord with
                    the President’s memoranda of September 1, 1969<note n="4" xml:id="d141fn4">
                        <ref target="#d70">Document 70.</ref>
                    </note> and December 21, 1970.<note n="5" xml:id="d141fn5">A copy is in the
                        National Security Council, Secretariat, Directives, 1970, Directive
                        #154.</note> All of the cables mentioned in your memorandum were handled in
                    accordance with these procedures. They do not in my view depart from policy
                    established by the President, and I therefore do not consider that the question
                    of policy implication arises.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">William P. Rogers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
